# SKILL INVOCATION

## Model-Invoked Nature

DECLARE invocation_pattern: object
SET invocation_pattern = {
"type": "automatic",
"trigger": "Claude analyzes description and decides when to apply",
"user_action": "None required - happens automatically",
"distinction": "Skills ≠ Slash Commands (commands are user-invoked)"
}

## How Claude Decides to Use Skill

WHEN claude_processes_user_request:
ANALYZE request FOR keywords
EXTRACT intent FROM request

    FOR EACH skill IN available_skills:
        CALCULATE relevance_score = MATCH(request, skill.description)
        IF relevance_score > threshold:
            LOAD skill INTO context
            APPLY skill_knowledge TO request_processing

## Writing Effective Descriptions

DECLARE description_guidelines: object
SET description_guidelines = {
"be_specific": "Use concrete keywords Claude can match",
"define_triggers": "Specify when to use (not just what it does)",
"avoid_vague": "Don't use 'helps with' or 'useful for'",
"include_context": "Mention domain, framework, or problem type"
}

### Good vs Bad Descriptions

```
BAD:  "Helps with React development"
GOOD: "Use when implementing React components following our architecture"

BAD:  "Database skills"
GOOD: "Use when designing database schemas, writing migrations, or optimizing queries"

BAD:  "Debugging tool"
GOOD: "Use when investigating memory leaks in Electron applications"
```

VALIDATION GATE: Invocation Complete
✅ Model-invoked nature explained
✅ Decision process documented
✅ Description guidelines provided

# OPERAT

ALWAYS keep SKILL.md focused and under 500 lines
ALWAYS write clear, specific descriptions for model invocation
ALWAYS include practical examples for common scenarios
ALWAYS document pitfalls and how to avoid them
ALWAYS reference actual codebase files when applicable
ALWAYS use PAG keywords and structure
ALWAYS test that skill triggers correctly

NEVER use skills as slash commands (they are model-invoked)
NEVER assume skills inherit from main conversation (must be explicit)
NEVER create overly broad skills (keep focused on one domain)
NEVER skip examples - they teach application patterns
NEVER write vague descriptions (use concrete keywords)
NEVER exceed 500 lines without progressive disclosure
NEVER reference skills - embed knowledge directly

## Progressive Disclosure Trigger

WHEN skill_content > 500_lines:
CREATE subdirectory: ".claude/skills/skill-name/"
MOVE detailed_content TO separate_files
MAINTAIN overview IN SKILL.md
ADD cross_references BETWEEN files

# NOTES

- Skills teach capabilities, commands execute tasks
- Skills are model-invoked (automatic), not user-invoked
- Higher scopes override lower scopes in naming conflicts
- Skills do NOT inherit from main conversation context
- Progressive disclosure keeps main file scannable
- Description quality determines invocation accuracy
- Examples are critical for teaching application patterns
- PAG structure provides clarity and consistency
